Author: scifichick774<br>
Rating: PG-13<br>
Category: UST/Angst/ Humor/Romance Chloe/Lex<br>
Spoilers: Through Redux. Sequel to “The Lana Zone”.<br>
Summary: Lex helps Chloe come up with a new game to get Clark’s attention. But does he have an ulterior motive?<br>
Disclaimer: Not mine, no infringement intended, please don’t sue.<br>
Feedback: Yes please.<br>
Archival: Go ahead, just let me know where.<br>
Author’s Note: The beginning of this is a little angstier than the prequel, but it will get into the humor, I promise.<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Lex walked into the Talon and spotted Chloe sitting in one of the chairs in a back corner. He grinned. He hadn’t seen much of her since the last Lana zone game they played. She hadn’t even ended up joining them for dinner that night, because her dad called and gave her a guilt trip about not seeing her much lately. But now, Gabe was away at a conference and Chloe was sitting there all alone. Lex ordered his coffee and strolled over to her.<br>
<br>
“May I?” He asked. She looked up at him and he motioned to the chair next to her. He sat down without waiting for her reply.<br>
<br>
“Seeing as how you own the place, I doubt I could stop you,” she said. He arched an eyebrow at her.<br>
<br>
“Bad day?” Lex asked. Her expression softened and she gave him a small smile.<br>
<br>
“I’m sorry, I didn’t mean to take it out on you,” she said. He nodded once as an acceptance of her apology.<br>
<br>
“Would a rousing game of Lana zone cheer you up?” He asked. She chuckled morbidly.<br>
<br>
“I don’t think so,” she answered. “I think I need a new game.” She paused and looked thoughtful. “If I ask you a question, will you tell me the truth?” Lex grinned.<br>
<br>
“I didn’t realize this had turned into an interview,” he replied. She shook her head.<br>
<br>
“Not that kind of question,” she said. Chloe took a sip of her coffee and smiled. “If it was a question about you, then I would have expected you to lie.” He feigned hurt.<br>
<br>
“I think I’m insulted,” he said.<br>
<br>
“Don’t be. It was actually a compliment,” she said. He furrowed his brow at her.<br>
<br>
“How can calling me a liar be construed as a compliment exactly?” He asked. She shrugged.<br>
<br>
“You don’t open up your emotional wounds for everybody to dig at, you protect yourself. It’s a survival technique that I have yet to master,” she answered. Lex frowned, but quickly put on a neutral face.<br>
<br>
“What did you want to ask me?”<br>
<br>
“I’m having second thoughts about it now. Forget I said anything,” she said. Chloe brought her coffee up to her mouth and took a long drink so she could avoid talking to him, but he looked at her expectantly, and she knew she wouldn’t be able to get out of having the conversation. “If I ask you, it’s just going to make me look incredibly bitter and resentful, and I’d rather not portray myself in that light if you don’t mind.” Lex couldn’t help but smile.<br>
<br>
“I think I can handle it,” he said honestly. Chloe sighed.<br>
<br>
“Why does every guy in Smallville like Lana? You know, apart from the whole pretty and nice thing,” she said. He leaned forward in his chair and gave her a thoughtful expression.<br>
<br>
“Every guy or just a certain farm boy?” he answered. She frowned and closed her eyes for a second, and then she shook her head.<br>
<br>
“Right now I almost wish it was just Clark,” she said.<br>
<br>
“I’m sure that some of the male population of Smallville hasn’t fallen for the raven haired beauty,” he replied. She gave him a blank expression.<br>
<br>
“And by the way you answered that question, I can tell that obviously isn’t the case,” she said. Chloe started to stand up and Lex touched her arm to stop her.<br>
<br>
“You’re leaving?” He asked. His mind went through a dozen things he could tell her that would make her stay. “We haven’t come up with a new game yet.” She turned and looked at him and he offered a partial smile. She forced a smile onto her face too.<br>
<br>
“Don’t need one,” she announced. “I’ve decided to give up on men and join a convent.” Lex laughed.<br>
<br>
“You’d never make it through the vow of silence,” he joked. Her lips went thin and she glared at him. She wanted so badly to be angry with him, but she just couldn’t. Finally, she just smiled.<br>
<br>
“Maybe they’ll let me skip that one,” she said. Lex smiled and moved his eyes back to the chair she had been in, indicating that she should sit down. He smirked.<br>
<br>
“Somehow I doubt it,” he said. Chloe sat down and shook her head.<br>
<br>
“What do you suggest then?” She asked. Lex raised his eyebrows.<br>
<br>
“You’re asking me for advice?” He asked in surprise. She grinned.<br>
<br>
“I know. That’s one of the signs of the apocalypse isn’t it?” She kidded. Lex nodded and grinned.<br>
<br>
“It very well could be,” he said. “But I’ll be happy to give you advice.” She crossed her arms and smiled at him.<br>
<br>
“Okay,” she said. “What is it?”<br>
<br>
“I think you should give all your attention to a man other than Clark,” he said. She arched an eyebrow. “You don’t have to like him,” he added.<br>
<br>
“You’re joking?” She asked. He shook his head.<br>
<br>
“See it as the new game you wanted. Any time Clark is around, you spend the entire conversation talking about your new paramour, or, if he’s there, doting on him,” Lex said.<br>
<br>
“You want me to try and make Clark jealous?” She asked in disbelief. “Because it won’t work. I think we’ve already established that.”<br>
<br>
“It’s not a matter of making Clark jealous, it’s a matter of putting yourself in a mind set where he’s no longer the first thing you think about.” Lex paused and smiled. “And there’s the added bonus of seeing Clark’s reaction.” Chloe laughed.<br>
<br>
“You’re not going to let me leave here until I agree to this are you?” She asked. Lex smirked.<br>
<br>
“Never let it be said that you weren’t intelligent,” he responded. She rolled her eyes.<br>
<br>
“Fine. And who do you suggest my new ‘paramour’ should be?” Chloe asked. Lex smiled brightly at her and all of a sudden she felt very unsettled.<br>
<br>
“You’re going to let me choose?” He asked, the delight evident in his voice.<br>
<br>
“It’s your game, your rules,” she replied. The gleam in his eye was unnerving.<br>
<br>
“Well, in that case, me.”<br>
