<br>
“He’s not your type,” he said. Chloe frowned.<br>
<br>
“I’ve been thinking about changing my type,” she said. “I’m sick of liking good looking farm boys who only lust after girls with dark hair and the initials ‘L, L’.” Pete laughed.<br>
<br>
“Hey, I’m all for supporting that decision,” he said and winked at her. She chuckled.<br>
<br>
“We haven’t come up with a name for the game yet. I just told him that I needed a new game besides Lana zone because it was getting too depressing,” Chloe finally answered. Pete glanced at her as he was driving.<br>
<br>
“Okay, so what are the rules?” He asked. She shook her head.<br>
<br>
“I’m not sure you’ll believe me if I tell you,” she said.<br>
<br>
“I’m not sure I’ll be able to restrain myself from killing Luthor if you don’t,” he said tongue in cheek. Chloe sniggered.<br>
<br>
“Fine,” she agreed. “I have to give all my attention to a man other than Clark. I don’t have to like him.” Pete raised his eyebrows.<br>
<br>
“And you picked Lex?” He asked in surprise. Chloe snorted.<br>
<br>
“No. His game, his rules. He chose,” she said. “Any time Clark is around I have to spend the entire time doting on him or talking about him if he isn’t there.” Pete grumbled.<br>
<br>
“Sounds like a sweet deal for Lex,” he commented. Chloe smiled and shook her head.<br>
<br>
“I don’t think so. I have a good feeling that I’m going to win,” she said.<br>
<br>
“And how do you win?” Pete asked as he pulled up to her house.<br>
<br>
“The first person to tell someone outside the game, being anyone other than you, me, or Lex, loses,” she said. “And that goes for you too, so don’t slip up and tell anybody or you’re going to owe Lex and I coffee.” Pete grinned.<br>
<br>
“At least it’s not dinner,” he said. Chloe nodded in agreement. Pete sighed. He wondered why Chloe couldn’t see through Lex’s pathetic excuse for a game. It was obvious that Lex liked her and was just using her stubborn and competitive nature to get her close to him. But, as long as Chloe wanted to play, he would go along with it. Besides, if they had more run-ins with Victoria or any other snooty rich people, it would be worth it just to see the looks on their faces. Maybe this would be a fun game after all.<br>
Chloe said goodbye to Pete and ran into her house. Gabe smiled at her from the couch when she came in.<br>
<br>
“Hi sweetheart,” he greeted. She went over to him and gave him a small hug.<br>
<br>
“Hi Dad,” she replied. Chloe took a good look at the expression on his face. “What?” She asked. Gabe leaned forward.<br>
<br>
“Mr. Luthor called for you,” he said. She tried not to let her eyes grow wide or let the string of profanities that was running through her head slip out of her mouth.<br>
<br>
“Oh?” She asked as non-chalantly as she could. “What did Lex have to say?” Gabe shook his head.<br>
<br>
“Not Lex,” he corrected. ‘Okay, this is bad,’ thought Chloe. “Lionel Luthor personally called and asked if you were free to join their family for dinner on Saturday.” Chloe grimaced.<br>
<br>
“You told him ‘no’ right?” She asked hopefully. Her dad looked bemused.<br>
<br>
“I thought you’d want to go,” he said. “You’ve been talking about wanting an interview with him for a couple of months now. Isn’t that what this is about?” Chloe’s mouth dropped open, but she turned it into a fake smile.<br>
<br>
“Probably,” she falsely agreed. “I’m just surprised that he finally gave in.” Gabe nodded.<br>
<br>
“Me too,” he said. “So behave yourself.”<br>
